<h5>
Presentation 1: Animal exploitation and liberation: into and within the
neoliberal world order
</h5>

<p>
Author:
Mina da Rui <br>
Speaker: Mina da Rui (University of Winchester)
</p>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
This is a social science-oriented paper informed by research on global
governance, political economy and critical studies of neoliberalism – both
as ideology and societal modus operandi. It considers the multivalent,
dynamic connections between mass animal exploitation and its economic
and socio-political ecosystem. The objective is to present, for the benefit of
animal advocates or academics not familiar with these considerations,
mutually reinforcing mechanisms such as negative conceptions of freedom,
zero-sum competition, and alienation, linking these two hallmarks of the
contemporary world – financialised, commodifying, extractive capitalism,
and the systematic exploitation and denial of autonomy inflicted upon most
animals – but also opportunities stemming from these. This reflection offers
a historical overview of connections between both phenomena, then
examines, with some comparison with other existing socio-political orders,
how neoliberalism shapes our relationships with animals, which may
provide helpful notions for animal advocates in their efforts to find effective
purchase points in their work.
</p>
