<h5>
Presentation 2: Institutional animal advocacy: a key finding from the
study of past social movements
</h5>

<p>
Author: Jamie Harris<br>
Speaker: Jamie Harris (Sentience Institute)
</h4>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>

<p>
Though animal advocates reference historical social movements to make
ethical arguments and occasionally to provide a basis for their strategy,
there is a deep well of strategic evidence that remains mostly untapped. I
present evidence from three case studies: the British antislavery
movement, European anti-GMO movement, and the U.S. anti-abortion
movement, which suggests that many social movements have had the
most success through institutional tactics. Consumer boycotts against
sugar and abortion pills seem to have helped activists achieve their goals
when used to apply pressure to specific institutions. However, generalised
consumer action such as the U.S. free produce movement’s boycott of
slave-made goods and, arguably, the “green consumerism” of the
environmental movement, have been less effective. These case studies,
taken together with recent survey evidence and the findings from
psychological research, provide compelling evidence that a shift to
institutional animal advocacy may lead to far larger social changes for
animals.
</p>
