<h5>
Presentation 4: Ideological bases of attitudes towards meat
abstention: Vegetarianism as a threat to the cultural and economic
status quo.
</h5>
<p>
Author: Samantha Stanley<br>
Speaker: Samantha Stanley (Australian National University)</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Political conservatives eat more meat and engage in more exploitation of
animals than political liberals. One explanation for this association is that
right-wing adherents are more attuned to the ways the veg*nism movement
may threaten their nation&#39;s traditions and economic system. To disentangle
the extent &#39;Veg*nism threat&#39; is driven by symbolic concerns (e.g. to cultural
traditions) and realistic (economic) concerns, I developed a measure that
distinctly captures each threat type in two nations with high per-capita meat
consumption: Australia (Study One, N = 197) and the United States (Study
Two, N = 440). My findings suggest that symbolic concerns are the key
element of veg*nism threat contributing to negative attitudes towards meat
abstention and its proponents, meaning that a key obstacle to acceptance
of meat abstention (and its proponents) is the fear of disrupting the societal
status quo.
</p>

